            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "[GUfuncs require a signature](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/c-api/generalized-ufuncs.html#details-of-signature), such as `(m?,n),(n,p?)->(m?,p?)` for `np.matmul`, which you could parse to check which function arguments would be inputs and which outputs.  This would be a required argument passed to a dedicated gufunc decorator, or perhaps the presence or absence of the signature would tell Cython whether to generate a standard UFunc or a generalized UFunc.  I don't think you can avoid requiring the signature unless you come up with another way to say which axes of which arguments should be the same length and how those affect the output.\n\nRe: the allocation concern: I like the idea of passing the output arrays as arguments, it saves me from having to work out how to allocate memory that will last past the end of the function, since I've had to look that up every time I needed to do so.  ",
